{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox Institute |name = Kihara Institute for Biological Research |image = Yokohama-City-Univ-Maioka-2011120402.jpg |image_size = |image_name = |caption = |established = 1942 |chairman = |head_label = Director/Dean |head = Yasunari Ogihara, PhD |faculty = |staff = |budget = |endowment = |debt = |location = [[Totsuka-ku, Yokohama]] |address = 641-12 Maioka, Totsuka, Yokohama 244-0813, Japan |website = {{URL|http://www.yokohama-cu.ac.jp/kihara}} }}
The {{nihongo|'''Kihara Institute for Biological Research'''|横浜市立大学木原生物学研究所|Yokohama Shiritsu Daigaku Kihara Seibutsugaku Kenkyūjo}} ('''KIBR''') is an ancillary establishment of [[Yokohama City University]] in [[Yokohama]], Japan. The KIBR was founded in 1942 by [[Hitoshi Kihara]] to promote [[biological research]] in Japan. The Institute maintains a store of genetic resources - about 6,000 varieties of [[wheat]] and 800 of [[capsicum]] (chili peppers).<ref>[http://www.jica.go.jp/regions/africa/ku57pq00001la1es-att/60_yokohama_city_univ_intl_management.pdf Graduate School of International Management Yokohama City University | JICA]{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==Research== Although the KIBR's primary focus is [[plant biology]], research there covers a wide variety of biological fields, including [[biochemistry]], [[cell biology]], [[genetics]], [[Informatics (academic field)|informatics]], and [[biotechnology]]. The results of the research conducted at KIBR are regularly published in peer reviewed publications.
==Education== In addition to being a [[research institute]], the KIBR functions as an institution of higher education, constituting the Graduate School of [[Nanobioscience]], Yokohama City University. The graduate school offers a five-year doctoral program and a two-year master course for university graduates.<ref name="history">{{cite web |url= http://www.yokohama-cu.ac.jp/kihara/outline/kiharaenkaku.html|script-title=ja:木原生物学研究所の沿革|trans-title=History of the Kihara Institute for Biological Research|date= |work= |publisher= Yokohama City University|location= Japan|language= Japanese|accessdate= 28 January 2014}}</ref>
==Organization== *Department of Plant Genetic Resource (Prof. Tomohiro Ban) *Department of Plant Genome Science (Prof. Yasunari Ogihara) *Department of Plant Biotechnology (Prof. Yukihisa Shimada) *Plant Functional Genomics Research Group (Visiting Prof. Minami Matsui) *Plant Genomic Network Research Team (Visiting Prof. Motoaki Seki) *Plant Genome Engineering Research Unit (Visiting Prof. Seiichi Toki) *Kihara Memorial Room
==History== Founded in May 1942 in [[Kyoto]] by [[Hitoshi Kihara]], known for the proposal of the [[genome]] theory,<ref>[http://kihara.or.jp/english/kihara/dr_kihara.html About Our Founder]</ref> the KIBR moved to [[Minami-ku, Yokohama]] in May 1957.<ref name="history"/> The institute was able to remain open and continue its work throughout the Second World War. It became an ancillary establishment of [[Yokohama City University]] in April 1984, and relocated to the Maioka Research Park in [[Totsuka-ku, Yokohama]] in December 1994.<ref name="history"/>
On 15 September 2010, the institute was visited by the [[Emperor of Japan]] [[Akihito]] and [[Empress Michiko]].<ref>[http://www.kunaicho.go.jp/activity/gonittei/01/h22/gonittei-1-2010-3.html 天皇皇后両陛下のご日程 Schedule of Emperor and Empress of Japan] {{ja icon}}</ref>
==Kihara Memorial Room== The Kihara Memorial Room exhibits historical records of [[Hitoshi Kihara]] and has been open at the KIBR since 4 March 2010. The opening ceremony was attended by [[Fumihito, Prince Akishino]].<ref>[http://www.kunaicho.go.jp/activity/gonittei/03/h22/gonittei-3-2010-1.html 秋篠宮家のご日程 Schedule of Fumihito, Prince Akishino] {{ja icon}}</ref>
